ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-1 The pilot took off from Bassett, Nebraska, in a misty, light rain, at about 1930 central standard time (cst), en route to Valentine, Nebraska [60 miles away]. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-2 At approximately 2100 cst, the airport manager at Valentine received a telephone call from the pilot's sister, inquiring as to her brother's whereabouts. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-3 The airport manager called the fixed base operator at Bassett. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-4 The pilot's sister contacted the Cherry County, Nebraska, Sheriff's Department, and reported the pilot missing. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-5 The Nebraska Wing of the Civil Air Patrol (CAP), began an aerial search for the pilot's airplane at 2240 cst. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-6 The search was terminated 30 minutes later, when the CAP pilot began picking up ice on the airplane at 1,000 feet above ground level (agl). 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-7 The aerial search was re-convened the following morning. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-8 The wreckage was found at approximately 0830 cst. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-9 The Aviation Routine Weather Report (METAR) station at Ainsworth, Nebraska, at 1952 cst, reported an overcast ceiling of 3,400 and 10 miles visibility. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-10 The sheriff, who was part of the ground search the night of the accident, described the weather as being a mixture of freezing drizzle, rain, and snow, with low clouds and low ceilings. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-11 On arrival at the accident site the following day, the sheriff said that he felt ice on the surface of one of the airplane's wings. 
ntsb3434txt-1-5-5-0-12 Examination of the wreckage revealed no anomalies. 
